Reasoning: The paper deals with the relationship between randomized communication complexity and randomized decision tree complexity, which are both central topics in computational complexity theory. Therefore, cs.CC (Computational Complexity) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also involves information theory concepts such as index gadgets, which suggests cs.IT (Information Theory) as a likely sub-category. The use of decision trees and boolean functions points towards cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics), respectively. Finally, the paper may also be relevant to cs.CR (Cryptography and Security) due to its implications for query complexity separations involving randomized models.
